{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.11.2.1 Clearly Inferior Opponents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Defeating clearly inferior opponents neither teaches you anything nor significantly enhances your reputation; you are ineligible for a {\b benefit of victory} if the {\b resistance} you used in the contest exceeded the {\b resistance} by 6 or more. If, in the case of long contest, you or your opponent used multiple {\b abilities}, compare the best {\b ability} you used to his worst.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.11.3 Recovery and Healing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Consequences of {\b injured} or less lapse on their own with the passage of time. However, you\u8217'll often want to remove them ahead of schedule, with the use of {\b abilities}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.11.3.1 Healing Abilities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b ability} used to bring about recovery from a {\b state of adversity} must relate to the type of harm.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can heal physical injuries with medical or extraordinary {\b abilities}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can remove mental traumas, including those of confidence and morale, with mundane psychology or through {\b extraordinary abilities}. You might also remove then through a dramatic confrontation between the victim and the source of the psychic injury.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You use social abilities to heal social injuries. You probably have to make a public apology of some sort, often including a negotiation with the offended parties and the payment of compensation, either in disposable wealth or something more symbolic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can fix damage to items and equipment with some sort of repair {\b ability}. If you want to fix an extraordinary item, you may require genre-specific expertise: a broken magic ring may require a ritual to reforge.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM should almost always resolve healing attempts as {\b simple contest}s. An exception might be a medical drama, in which surgeries would comprise the suspenseful set-piece sequences of the game, and your GM might chose an {\b long contest}.\par}
