{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.5.2 Consequences and Benefits\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Depending on which approach seems to grow from the story, your GM may assign {\b consequences of defeat} or {\b benefits of victory} from Group Simple Contests to the entire group, or to individual members who performed either especially well, or especially poorly. Your GM should default to rewarding or penalizing everyone. Your GM should resort to individualized repercussions or benefits only when a group reward defies dramatic credibility, or when competition within the group is a pivotal dramatic issue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.5.3 Boosting Outcomes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Because they average together the {\b outcomes} of multiple participants, {\b group simple contests} tend to flatten {\b outcomes}, making {\b victories} more likely to be {\b marginal} or {\b minor} than {\b major} or {\b complete}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To overcome this flattening effect, you can, at the beginning of a {\b group simple contest}, spend one or more {\b hero points} to purchase a {\b boost}. A {\b boost} assures a clearer {\b victory}, should you prevail.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The cost varies by the number of heroes participating:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 {\b hero point} for 1-3 heroes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 2 {\b hero points} for 4-6 heroes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 3 {\b hero points} for 7-9 heroes.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab and so on\u8230?\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may spend twice as many {\b hero points} as required to gain a {\b double boost}. The points may be spent by any combination of players. They remain spent no matter how the {\b contest} resolves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On a tie or a victory, the {\b boost} increases the collective victory level by one step. A {\b double boost} increases it by two steps.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 5. (Advanced) Long Contests\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Most conflicts should be resolved simply and quickly, using the {\b simple contest} rules.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, every so often, your GM wants to stretch out a resolution, breaking it down into a series of smaller actions, increasing the suspense you feel as you wait to see if they succeed or fail.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Think of the different ways a film director can choose to portray a given moment, depending on how important it is to the story, and how invested he wants us to feel in its {\b outcome}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, there are two ways to shoot a scene in which a thief breaks into the bank to steal the contents of the safe.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The action can be portrayed quickly, cutting to a moment with the thief with their ear pressed against the safe trying to get the tumblers fall into place. Then he sighs with relief, opens the safe, and gets whatever is inside. In this instance, the story is about what happens after the thief gets what\u8217's in the safe, not about what might happen to him if he fails.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Another film might instead choose to make the bank robbery a pivotal turning point in the story, if not its climactic moment. It would spend many scenes building up to the safe-cracking sequence: obtaining the plans of the bank, learning the movements of the guards, crawling through the air conditioning ducts, sliding past the motion sensors and pressure plates, and finally cracking the safe itself. All of these scenes would be rounds of a long contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Remember that {\i QuestWorlds} uses conflict resolution. If you want to describe how you overcome a sequence of {\b story obstacles} to overcome the {\b resistance} then your GM should use a {\b long contest}, if you just want to move on to the next scene, use a {\b simple contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Even a movie driven by action and suspense will typically include only a handful of these set-piece sequences. They need the rest of their running times to build up to their big moments, to make us care about the characters, and to give us quiet moments to contrast with the white-knuckle parts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 So pacing may always trump your desire to work through the sequence of events, as your GM may wish to resolve this conflict quickly. This is especially true if only one player is involved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM may be tempted, to adjudicate every fight with a {\b long contest}, because fights seem like they should be played out blow-by-blow. They should resist this temptation, as fights are often repetitive exchanges of blows that can drag when everyone repeats actions from round to round. Only use *long contests** for fights where the PCs want to do more than slug it out toe-to-toe with their opponents until only one is left standing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are three types of {\b long contest}. Your GM should chose one to use with their campaign: {\b scored contest}, {\b extended contest}, or {\b chained contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.1 Scored Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Scored contests} are longer and more dramatic than {\b simple contests}. Your GM uses {\b scored contests} when the {\b outcome} of the struggle is important, to generate suspense for you, or when your GM want a back-and-forth struggle. It is something you and your GM should visualize and describe.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b scored contest} consists of one or more {\b rounds}, in which you perform actions that are similar to {\b simple contests}. However, actions and {\b rounds} do not decide the {\b outcome} of the whole {\b contest}, only who gains or loses {\b resolution points} at that time. In a {\b scored contest} there is no distinction between aggressor and defender, each {\b round} represents attempts by both parties to overcome their opponent. Your GM should determine who has the initiative to describe what they are doing for any {\b exchange}, based on their interpretation of the flow of events. If in doubt your GM should defer to you over your opponent to describe what you do in the {\b round}, and describe the NPC reacting to that.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.1.1 Procedure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Your GM {\b frames the contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab You choose a {\b tactic}, and figure your PC\u8217's {\b target number} ({\b TN}) using the {\b rating} of your {\b ability}, plus or minus {\b modifiers} the GM may give you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Your GM determines the {\b resistance}. If two PCs contend, your opponent figures their {\b TN} as described in step 2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Carry out one or more {\b rounds}, repeating as necessary.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab An {\b scored contest} unfolds as a series of {\b simple contests}. At the end of each {\b simple contest}, the winner scores a number of {\b resolution points (RPs)} to their tally, which varies between 1 and 5, depending on the {\b result}. Tied {\b results} leave the score unchanged.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Your GM decides which opponent has the initiative and describes what they are trying to do to achieve the prize, the \u8216'aggressor\u8217'. The \u8216'defender\u8217' describes how they counter the aggressor\u8217's attempt to sieze the prize. If it is not obvious from the unfolding narrative, your GM should choose your PC as a the \u8216'aggressor\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Conduct a simple contest as normal, but once the {\b outcome} has been determined, it becomes a number of {\b resolution points} scored by the winning side.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab The number of {\b resolution points} the winner garners at the end of each exchange depends on the degree of victory they scored. They get 1 point for a marginal victory, 2 for a minor victory, 3 for a major victory, and 5 for a complete victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab The first to accumulate a total of 5 points wins; their opponent is knocked out of the {\b contest} and loses the {\b prize}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Determine the {\b scored contest outcome} based on {\b rising action} of Climax (below).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Determine {\b benefits of victory} or {\b consequences of defeat}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 7.\tx360\tab Describe the {\b outcome} based on the {\b story obstacle}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike in an {\b extended contest} (see below), where you usually take part in two {\b exchanges} with your opponent per {\b round} (one in which you choose the {\b AP bid}, and one in which your opponent does), here you and your opponent engage in a single {\b exchange} per round (in which whoever the GM determines has initiative describes an action to sieze the prize and their opponent how they intend to stop them).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your {\b resolution point} score tells you how well you\u8217're doing, relative to your opponent, in the ebb and flow of a fluid, suspenseful conflict. If you\u8217're leading your opponent by 0\u8211-4, you\u8217're giving him a thorough pasting. If you\u8217're behind 4\u8211-0, you\u8217're on your last legs, while your opponent has had an easy time of it. If you\u8217're tied, you\u8217've each been getting in some good licks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a fight, scoring 1 RP might mean that you hit your opponent with a grazing blow, or knocked him into an awkward position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Scoring 2 RPs might mean a palpable hit, most likely with bone-crunching sound effects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A 3-RP hit sends him reeling, and, depending on the realism level of the genre, may be accompanied by a spray of blood.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the exact physical harm you\u8217've dished out to him remains unclear until the {\b contest\u8217's} end. When that happens, the real effects of your various victories become suddenly apparent. Perhaps he staggers, merely dazed, up against a wall. Maybe he falls over dead.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a debate, a 1 RP might occasion mild head nodding from spectators, or a frown on your opponent\u8217's face.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 2 RPs would occasion mild applause from onlookers, or send a flush to your opponent\u8217's face.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On 3-RPs, your opponent might be thrown completely off-track, as audience members wince at the force of your devastating verbal jab.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In interpreting the individual simple {\b contests} within an {\b scored contest}, Narrators are guided by two principles:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab No consequence is certain until the entire {\b scored contest} is over.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab When a character scores points, it can reflect any positive change in fortunes, not just the most obvious one.\sa180\par}
