{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.1.2 Rising Action\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rising action} refers to all of the many plot events and complications that occur between the beginning and the climax of a story. During this phase of your GM\u8217's story, they will use the {\b rising action} Consequence table to assess {\b outcomes}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Find the difference between you and your opponent\u8217's {\b resolution point} scores at the {\b contest}\u8217's conclusion. Your GM then determines your {\b outcome} by cross-referencing with the following table to find the {\b benefits of victory} or {\b consequences of defeat}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you engage multiple opponents in a {\b rising action scored contest}, only use the last opponent you engaged to determine your individual {\b outcome}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note, that as with all {\b contests}, we care about your {\b outcome}, win or lose, and the GM will narrate the {\b outcome} for the {\b resistance}, which may not be symmetrical. You may suffer a {\b consequence}, even if you win.\par}
