{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.4 Followers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may choose to have your followers take part in Group {\b scored contests} in one of three ways: as full contestants, as secondary contestants, or as supporters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contestant}: The follower takes part in the contest as any other PC would. You roll for your followers as you would their main characters. However, your followers are removed from the contest whenever 3 {\b resolution points} are scored against them in a given {\b round}. An additional 2 {\b resolution points are then scored against them, increasing the severity of any consequences they suffer. } {\b Secondary contestant}: To act as a secondary contestant, your follower must have an {\b ability} relevant to the contest. The follower sticks by your side, contributing directly to the effort: fighting in a battle, tossing in arguments in a legal dispute, acting as the ship\u8217's navigator, or whatever. Although you describe this, you do not roll for the follower. Instead, you may, at any point, shift any number of {\b resolution points} to a follower acting as a secondary contestant. Followers with 3 or more points lodged against them are removed from the scene. When a follower is removed from the scene, an additional 2 {\b resolution points} are lodged against them, increasing the severity of consequences they suffer. You lose the protection against multiple opponents afforded by the follower.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Supporter}: Your follower is present in the scene, but does not directly engage your opponents. Instead they may perform {\b assists} and other {\b unrelated actions}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Followers acting in any of these three capacities may be removed from the contest by otherwise unengaged opponents. To remove a follower from a scene, an opponent engages your follower in a Simple Contest. Your GM sets the {\b resistance}, or if it is another PC\u8217's follower they determines the relevant {\b ability} of the follower engaging yours. On any failure, your follower is taken out of the contest. For consequence determination purposes, the follower has X+2 {\b resolution points} lodged against him, where X is the usual number levied by the {\b resolution point} table.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.5 Risky Gambits\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 During a {\b scored contest}, you can attempt to force a conflict to an early resolution by making a {\b risky gambit}. If you win the {\b round}, you lodge an additional 1 {\b resolution point} against your opponent. However, if you lose the {\b round}, your opponent lodges an additional 2 {\b resolution points} against you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If both contestants engage in a {\b risky gambit}, the winner lodges an additional 2 {\b resolution points} against the loser.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.6 Defensive Responses\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a {\b scored contest}, you can make a {\b defensive response}, lowering the number of {\b resolution points} lodged against you in an {\b round}. If you win the {\b round}, the number of {\b resolution points} you lodge against your opponent decreases by 1. If you lose, your opponent lodges 2 fewer {\b resolution points} against you. The total number of {\b resolution points} assigned by an {\b round} is never less than 0; there is no such thing as a negative {\b resolution point}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.7 Joining Scored Contests In Progress\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you wish to join an {\b scored contest} in progress, you and your GM should discuss whether you accept the current framing. If so, you can participate. In an {\b scored contest}, you simply select an opponent and enters into a new {\b round}. If you want to achieve something other than the goal established during framing, you may instead perform {\b unrelated actions}, including {\b assists} and {\b augments}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.8 Switching Abilities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may describe an action in a {\b scored contest} that is not covered by the {\b ability} that you started the contest with. There are two possibilities here: either you are trying to provide color to your actions in the {\b round}, without seeking to gain advantage, or you are seeking to gain advantage over your opponent with a novel {\b tactic}. In the former case, you can continue to use the {\b ability} you started the contest with, as you should not be penalized for wanting to enhance the contest with colorful or entertaining descriptions. In the latter case you should switch {\b abilities}, and your GM must decide if the {\b resistance} changes because of your new {\b ability}. Your GM is encouraged to reward {\b tactics} that exploit weaknesses that have been identified in the story so far with a lower {\b resistance}. Sometimes your GM may respond with a higher {\b resistance} because your {\b tactic} looks less likely to succeed due to conditions already established in the story.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.3 Extended Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Extended contests} are longer and more dramatic than simple contests. Your GM uses {\b extended contests} when the {\b outcome} of the struggle is important, to generate suspense for the players, or when they want a back-and-forth struggle. It is something you and your GM should visualize and describe.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An extended contest consists of one or more {\b rounds}, in which you perform actions that are similar to simple contests. However, actions and {\b rounds} do not decide the {\b outcome} of the whole contest, only who gains or loses advantage points (AP) at that time. You take actions in turn, losing and gaining the advantage, until either you or your opponent runs out of advantage points and is defeated.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.3.1 Procedure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Your GM {\b frames the contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab You choose a {\b tactic}, and figure your PC\u8217's {\b target number} ({\b TN}) using the {\b rating} of your {\b ability}, plus or minus {\b modifiers} the GM may give you. Figure your starting Advantage Point (AP) total using the {\b TN}, including all {\b modifiers} and {\b augments}. The AP include +20 for each level of {\b mastery}, and can also be increased by followers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab The GM determines the {\b resistance}. The GM opposes the PC with a {\b resistance}\u8212-the harder the task or tougher the opponent, the higher the {\b resistance}. The Narrator figures starting {\b APs} for the {\b resistance} from the {\b resistance} {\b TN}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Carry out one or more {\b rounds}, repeating as necessary.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Each {\b round} consists of two {\b exchanges}: an action and immediate response.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Describe your action towards the desired {\b prize}, what {\b ability} you uses, and how much risk you take. \u8220"I want to climb straight up to that outcrop, taking chances if needed.\u8221" You can specify your {\b AP bid}; if you do not, your GM determines this based on the amount of risk you are taking. The size of the bid mirrors how bold and risky your character\u8217's action is. Extreme or aggressive actions mean a high {\b AP bid}, and cautious actions require less.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab The {\b ability} used can be varied, but {\b APs} are always calculated on the first {\b ability} that you use in a contest. That {\b ability} must be used in the first {\b round}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab You gamble a number of your {\b APs} in an attempt to reduce your opponent\u8217's AP, but if you fail the attempt you lose the AP.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Roll a die to determine the your {\b degree of victory or defeat}, then apply any {\b bumps}. Your GM does the same.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Compare the results of the two die rolls on the Extended Contest Table to determine who loses AP; only when you have a critical can you gain AP from your opponent. The {\b AP bid} is multiplied by this number before applying the results. Thus, if you {\b bid} 3 AP and the result is \u8220"Opponent loses 2x {\b bid},\u8221" the loser loses 3 x 2 = 6 AP. Round half points up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Determine Contest Outcome. Each contestant\u8217's AP total rises or falls during the contest as they gains the upper hand or are driven back. Exchanges continue until one contestant reaches 0 advantage points or fewer. At that point, the contest is over (even if it is the middle of a {\b round}). The loser\u8217's final AP total determines the {\b outcome} for the victor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 7.\tx360\tab The GM then hazards a number of {\b APs} for the {\b resistance}, in the same way.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Advantage points are only relevant for the length of a particular {\b contest}. Your PC does not have any until the next {\b extended contest} begins, when you calculate them all over again\sa180\par}
