{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.3.3 Group Extended Contests\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When an {\b extended contest} involves three or more contestants, it is a {\b group extended contest}. The conflict is often between two groups; each side wants to knock the other out of the contest by reducing all of its opponents to 0 or fewer {\b APs}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes a contest will be a free-for-all involving three or more groups.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Rounds in a {\b group extended contest} differ in that the order of resolution is more complicated. At the start of the {\b round}, you state your action and {\b AP bid} and single out one or more opponents. Your GM then determines the order in which the contestants act. Taking surprise, withdrawals, and similar situations into effect, she has three options:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Contestants can go in order from most daring to least daring {\b bid}: a reckless {\b bid} goes before a daring {\b bid}, as defined in \u8220"Bidding Advantage Points\u8221" above. Thus, the most heroic actions take precedence, acting in order of decreasing boldness. (In case of a tie, the contestant whose actual {\b bid} is higher goes first.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Contestants can go in order from highest {\b bid} to lowest: a {\b bid} of 20 {\b APs} goes before a {\b bid} of 5 {\b APs}. (In case of a tie, the contestant whose {\b bid} is the most daring goes first.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Contestants can go in order from highest to lowest {\b AP} total. (In case of a tie, the highest or most daring {\b bid} goes first.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 During a standard {\b extended contest} an opponent immediately responds to your action with their own, but in a {\b group extended contest} this is not true\u8212-they cannot act (against you or anyone else) until their turn comes. You may want to change your declared action if another character attacks you first, and your GM will normally allow you to do so, usually to return an attack in kind.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The order in which contestants act is also important because a character (whether hero, opponent, or a follower of either) can be knocked out of the contest before their turn comes. If your chosen opponent is knocked out before your PC acts, the narrator decides if you can change your declared action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You always have the option of delaying and allowing other contestants to act before you. You can jump back into the action at any time during the {\b round}, although again your GM determines if you can change your stated action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When all characters still in the contest have completed their action the {\b round} ends and a new one begins.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.3.4 Parting Shot\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you defeat an opponent in an {\b extended contest}, you can act again immediately to try to make the consequences of his defeat more severe. This is called a {\b parting shot}. You once again {\b bid} AP and use an appropriate {\b ability} against your opponent. If you succeed, his AP will decrease; his level of defeat may or may not change, but he cannot finish the {\b round} by taking an action against you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Parting shots} are risky; if you fail, an AP transfer might bring your opponent back into the contest. Your stumble can give him an opening that he can exploit in an effort to snatch victory from the jaws of defeat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b consequences of defeat} can remain after a {\b parting shot}, if the narrator chooses. Thus, an opponent might keep a {\b penalty} from a defeat even if he is handed another chance by his opponent\u8217's failed {\b parting shot}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.3.5 Final Action\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your PC falls to 0 or fewer advantage points in a standard {\b extended contest}, you are defeated. In a {\b group extended contest}, however, you can still try a {\b final action} to stay in the contest as long as you are not dying (which allows for no actions). A {\b final action} represents the knack to come back when your opponent turns away to gloat or deal with the other heroes. A character may only attempt one {\b final action} in any contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To attempt a {\b final action}, you must be free from attention by the opposition. You must spend a {\b hero point}. This does not provide a bump up on the roll to come; it is the cost of performing a {\b final action}. You can use a relevant {\b ability} in a simple contest against the number of {\b APs} your hero is below 0. Even if you succeed, the consequences of the original defeat still apply: a {\b hurt} still takes a \u8211-1 to appropriate abilities until healed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you win the {\b simple contest}, you rejoin the contest with a positive {\b AP} total. Your new total is a fraction of the your original {\b AP} total at the outset of the contest. If you fail the {\b simple contest}, your {\b AP} total drops even further, perhaps worsening your consequences.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM should not use a {\b final action} for the {\b resistance} (and has no hero points for this anyway).\par}
