{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.4 Chained Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Chained Contests do not defer {\b consequences} to the end of the {\b contest}, instead applying the {\b consequences of defeat} to the loser in the {\b contest} immediately following a {\b round}. This leads to a grittier feel to the {\b contest}, but at the price of a death spiral: once you lose the {\b penalty} from losing makes it likelier that you will lose again.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To run an {\b extended contest} your GM runs a {\b simple contest} as normal, and then applies the {\b outcomes} according to the following table, withe the {\b consequences} taking immediate effect.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You decide if you wish to continue the contest, and your GM makes a similar determination for the {\b resistance}. Both you and your GM then express your intent, If your or your GM wishes to continue, play out another {\b simple contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you, or your GM, wishes to {\b disengage}, then on any {\b victory} you leave the contest, without inflicting consequences on the opposition. If both you and the GM wish to leave the contest, then you both {\b disengage}, and the contest ends. If any contestant is reduced to a {\b complete defeat}, the {\b contest} ends automatically.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Chained Contests are the simplest form of {\b long contest}, and you may prefer them for that reason. They also tend to produce the most extreme {\b outcomes}, as participants tend to continue until {\b complete defeat}.\par}
