{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 8.2 Drawing on Resources\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can use community {\b resources} as {\b ablities} after convincing the community to let you expend precious assets. This requires a preliminary {\b contest} using a social {\b ability}, most likely your community relationship. Your GM will use a {\b moderate resistance} as the baseline, with higher {\b resistance}s when your proposals seem selfish or likely to fail, and lower ones when everyone but the dullest dolt would readily see their collective benefits. your GM may increase {\b resistance}s if your group draws constantly on community {\b resources} without replenishing them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The lobbying effort and the actual resource use require framing, a clear description of what you are doing, and other details to bring them to fictional life. You can use {\b resource abilties} directly, or to {\b augment} your own {\b abilities}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike character abilities, each use of community {\b resources} temporarily {\b depletes} it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On a victory, you win the {\b prize} specified by {\b contest framing}, and a {\b penalty} is applied to subsequent uses of the {\b resource}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On a defeat, you lose the {\b prize} and an even more severe {\b penalty} is applied to subsequent {\b resource} uses. If you fail to secure the {\b prize} you were seeking, the depletion {\b penalty} is also applied to your social and community {\b abilities} when interacting with members of your community. This reflects community displeasure at your fruitless expenditure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Penalties} from the Resource Depletion Table replace standard {\b penalties} for defeat, not add to them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Like other {\b modifiers} to {\b resources}, depletion {\b penalties} end at the end of the current interval. These include {\b depletion penalties} applied to character {\b abilities}. However, a {\b depletion penalty} left unattended at the end of the interval can result in a permanent drop in the relevant {\b resource}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your GM wants resource depletion to lead to longer-lasting social {\b penalties} can, at the cost of some extra bookkeeping, they can have the characters shed a 3-point {\b penalty} at the end of each interval.\par}
